{"cursor":"5085","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{| class=\"infobox bordered\" style=\"width: 25em; text-align: left; font-\nsize: 95%;\"\n|+ style=\"font-size: larger;\" | 'Australian Baptist Ministries' - colspan=\"2\"\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" | \n|-\n! First Church:\n|   1835\n|-\n! President:\n|   Rev Dr John Beasy\n|-\n! Website:\n|   http://www.baptist.org.au/ -\n! International:\n Baptist World Alliance\n|}\nThe 'Australian Baptist Ministries' (ABM) (formerly 'Baptist Union of Australia'\n(BUA)) is the oldest and largest national cooperative body of Baptists in\nAustralia. Its current National President is Reverend Dr John Beasy.\n\nThe Baptist work in Australia began in Sydney in 1831, over forty years after\nthe British penal colony was established. The first preacher was John McKaeg.\nThe first baptism was in Woolloomooloo Bay in 1832. It was not until 1835 that\nthe first church was established in Hobart Town by Henry Dowling, a\nstrict Calvinist. John Saunders, sent by the Baptist Missionary Society of\nEngland, formed a church in 1836. The first state Union was formed in\nVictoria in 1862. The national Baptist Union was founded in 1926 by\nrepresentatives from existing state unions.\n\nThe Baptist Union of Australia is a member of the Asia Pacific Baptist\nFederation (formerly Asian Baptist Federation) and the Baptist World Alliance.\nMinistry arms of the BUA include the Global Interaction (formerly known as the\nAustralian Baptist Missionary Society), Australian Baptist World Aid, Baptist\nCare, and a number of Delegated Bodies which represent communities of practice,\ndeveloping strategies and resources that benefit the Australian Baptist\nmovement. These include: Crossover Australia, and Crossover Remote (formerly\nNorthreach) The national work is divided among seven state unions, which operate\nindependently, with the national body functioning as a governance council to\nfacilitate collaborative ministries and mission initiative across the Baptist\nmovement in Australia. In 2007, the Union comprised 61,409 members in 868\nchurches. The National Church Life Survey in 2001 estimated weekly\nattendance of Baptist Churches in Australia at 112,200.\n","linknr":227,"url":"Baptist_Union_of_Australia","recorded":1375059293,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Australian_Baptist_Ministries&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Australian_Baptist_Ministries&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Australian_Baptist_Ministries","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Baptist_Union_of_Australia&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","http://www.baptist.org.au/","/wiki/Baptist_World_Alliance","/wiki/Baptists","/wiki/Australia","/wiki/Sydney","/wiki/Woolloomooloo,_New_South_Wales","/wiki/Hobart","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Calvinist","/wiki/Baptist_Missionary_Society","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Victoria_(Australia)","/wiki/Asia_Pacific_Baptist_Federation","/wiki/Baptist_World_Alliance","/wiki/Australian_Baptist_World_Aid","#cite_note-3","/wiki/National_Church_Life_Survey","#cite_note-4","/wiki/Category:Baptist","/wiki/Baptists","/wiki/File:Baptism_logo.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/3a/Baptism_logo.jpg/100px-Baptism_logo.jpg","/wiki/Christianity","/wiki/Protestantism","/wiki/P